title: For Sale/Trade:  2006 Honda Ruckus and all accessories
location: Harris, MN, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: First- before I give you the details, let me address all the Icebear Ruckus clones out there. There is a reason the Ruckus has been copied by several Chinese companies. Its an awesome scooter. The engine in the clones is a copy of an OLD Honda design. But the quality is where they are lacking. Yes, you can buy a clone NEW for half the price of a Ruckus. Or you can buy one USED for next to nothing. Because they don't hold up. There is a subforum on TotalRuckus.com discussing the clones- and they are not even good for parts swaps onto the Ruckus, because even the parts are poor quality. There is no TotalIceBear.com or TotalTaoTao.com. Look at the mileage on my scooter. Over 13k, and that was all put on in less than three years. I trusted my Ruckus to take me to work and back EVERY DAY in rain (and snow, as rare as that was in Seattle) 16 miles EACH WAY. If the weather was nice or traffic was bad, I took a longer route home. I rode from Seattle to Portland and back, a two- day ride with friends- over 10 hours each day of continuous riding. A guy from Korea rode his Ruckus around the US in 2007, 17k miles in a year. You can read his blog on TotalRuckus.com. They hold up- the clone will not.So- I bought my Ruckus in 2007 with 1200 miles on it. It has 13k on it, but I rebuilt the engine at about 10k, with a new crank/bearing assembly. Not because of poor quality, but because of my parade riding habits of doing burnouts on the crosswalks. So you have a fresh engine that hasn't been abused. Has a chin bone made by Pomeruck. This is one of only SEVEN that Pome made, it is a solid mount at both ends, no pivots. So it actually does the job of triangulating the frame, it is NOT just for looks. Has a windscreen made by Chanito-san. At the time I installed it, I noted a 2mph increase in my top speed, more if I really tuck behind it. Frame extension to move the motor back 6 inches made by All ThatRuckus (now mostly known as ATR) Combined with the beefier rear shock, and added springs to beef up the front fork, this mod did WONDERS to smooth out the bumps. Has a CDI box to allow higher rpms, with a soft rev limiter at 10,500 (above which the valves can float and make contact).KN variator, with DR Pulley slider weights. Have a few different weights so you can tune it to your body weight and riding conditions for optimal speed and acceleration. Normal sizes are 5.5 and 6 grams, I accidentally was sent some 16 gram weights, which I have never used, I was thinking of using them if I ever bombed downhill from Paradise at Mt Rainier but that trip never materialized. Maybe you can use them. I also have a chrome-plated variator wrench so you don't strip or break anything when changing out your weights or changing belts.I also have a flywheel puller if you ever need to rebuild the engine, or plan to send your flywheel off to be lightened.Has a Gates Kevlar belt on it, pretty new but I'm throwing in two spare belts as well.Extra spark plugs and air filters. Extra airboxes, I swapped them out due to a defect in the sealing on my original. Still like running with the protection of a stock airbox. Lots of other extras- spare carb jets in various sizes, a whole set of Honda shims for your valves (if you have friends with ANY HONDA they can use these) Helmet with clear and tinted shields, winter and summer gloves, clear riding glasses, extra antifreeze, full shop manual, it all goes. There's probably stuff I forgot. We can talk if you're interested. This Ruck has a ton of history and I'll be sad to see it go. I was the organizer for Ruckus CON 2009 in Seattle, riders from Canada, Colorado, and the Rucksters crew from California all attended.Due to spammers and scammers, initial contact is by email only. Send any questions you have, or contact/ text info if you want to discuss.

title: For Sale:  RPB Mac 10/9 Open Bolt
location: Chesterfield / West County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
This is the REAL DEAL - An extremely rare 1981 MAC 10, RPB Industries Atlanta s.a.p. M10 "open bolt" 9mm. This gun is in basically unfired factory tested condition. It is clean as possible on the inside with virtually no scrape wear at all and no carbon fouling anywhere. It looks like it did in 1981. 
Comes with original box, original paperwork from 1981 - purchase receipt / County Police gun permit, six 32 round factory steel mags, fake suppressor, both versions of the factory manual, nomex suppressor sock that has never had the springs attached let alone stretched, original cleaning rod, mag loader, Assault Systems carry bag, sling and history book.
These were banned by the ATF in 1982 and can never be made again, but the select few stamped SAP M10 (semi automatic pistol) were grandfathered and considered exempt from this ruling. According to RPB there were fewer than 400 of these produced as most examples of these guns were sold to class 3 dealers and many of the small run marked SAP were actually converted to fully automatic weapons by class III manufactures.  It is possible only a handful are legitimately available today. This could be the only chance to own one of classic weapons in this mint condition.
 RPB manufactured the only semi auto open bolt variety of the M10 ever made, some were stamped "sM10" but a very few were made with the model stamped as "S.A.P. M10" (an abbreviation for semi auto pistol) This is a very rare variant of an extremely hard to come by pistol.   In 1979, Wayne Daniel manufactured a semi auto only version and somehow was able to get the BATF to approve it as a Title 1 firearm, that is, a regular gun. The open bolt semi auto M10 pistol manufactured by RPB were initially made using surplus SMG parts bought from Military Armaments Corporation when they went out of business in 1978.   The period of manufacture was very short lived however as in 1982 - the BATF reversed its decision on approving the open bolt semi auto guns when it was found that they were too easily converted to full auto. Effective June 21st 1982, any new M10's made as open bolt pistols were to be considered Title 2 firearms (i.e. machine guns)   These were produced for less than 3 years and can never be made again.   In case you don't believe that there is any way these rare guns can be legal please read the text of the ATF decision ruling 82-8 which banned any more of these from being made but allowed the ones already in existence as of the date of the ruling to be grandfathered in paragraph 6 of this ruling.   This is sold as a unique collectible pistol - you are responsible for complying with all state and federal laws - With that caveat we suggest that you don't do anything illegal with it - don't contemplate anything hypothetical, don't ask any STUPID questions, and don't discuss anything even slightly questionable even as a joke – we will NOT respond to any foolish emails containing illegal subject matter
This gun must be transferred thru an FFL and it is the buyers responsibility to comply with all laws – Cash only sale – no trades

title: For Sale:  .338 Lapua loaded
postcontent: I hate to part with my beloved .338 Lapua, but it needs a new home with someone who has more room to shoot it.  I sold my farm land, and now have nowhere to shoot it.  While the .50BMG may get a lot of the love from civilians, the .338 is lighter, shoots straighter, and is the prefered rifle of many sniper teams (military and law enforcement).  Note, this is the more sought out clamshell version, which is much easier on the wrist and easier to handle.This gun, the Savage 110 BA.338 Lapua, is the caliber of choice for many Navy Seal sniper teams.  Quoted from Chris Kyle regarding his .338 Lapua.  Hle recounts “I used a .338 on my last deployment. I would have used it more if I’d had it.” He goes on to say, “The bullet shoots farther and flatter than a .50 caliber, weighs less, costs less, and will do just about as much damage. They are awesome weapons.” He was obviously a big fan of the .338 Lapua, and the only drawback he mentioned was “my model’s lack of a suppressor. When you’re shooting inside a building, the concussion is strong enough that it’s a pain – literally. My ears would hurt after a few shots.”  The.338 Lapua was the rifle that he made his longest confirmed kill with, which was a 2,100 yard shot. postcontent:
For sale:  My H&R .22lr revolver.
Asking $160
6-shot .22lr revolver.  The cylinder is removed by pulling a pin that holds it in the frame- the pin pushes an extracter, then you load the new rounds.
-This firearm has indexing issues and is not working properly.  It should not be fired until the indexing issues are addressed.  It doesn't reliably go to lockup when the mainspring is cocked.  When it does lock up the cylinder is nice and tight.  There is a bit of fore-aft play in the cylinder which leads me to believe the ratchet is worn and the cylinder shoudl be replaced.  It is also possible the hand is at fault- I did replace the hand in the past and it was functioning reliably but lately it seems to have quit.  
On the bright side the nickel finish isn't terrible and the striker on the hammer is in good condition. The troublesome mainspring these sometimes have has been replaced with an all-metal one.
Fix it up and have a fun plinker.  I've had it apart before and it's not too difficult to work on.
I have a few other firearms listed- a yugo m57 and a remington 512 .22 rifle.  I would love to do a combined trade/cash deal if possible.  I'm looking for a working .22 revolver or auto loader.
 
Sale must be face to face and in a public place.  Cash only.  I'd prefer to meet at a show if possible.
